'''Ezri Ngoyo Konsa''' (born 23 October 1997) is an English professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[centre-back]] or [[right-back]] for {{English football updater|AstonVil}} club [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] and the [[England national football team|England national team]].

Konsa came through the academy at [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]], and later joined [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] and Aston Villa. He played for England at youth level, winning the [[2017 FIFA U-20 World Cup]] with the [[England national under-20 football team|under-20 team]] and the [[2018 Toulon Tournament]] with the [[England national under-21 football team|under-21s]], before making his senior debut in March 2024.

==Early life==
Ezri Ngoyo Konsa was born on 23 October 1997 in [[London Borough of Newham|Newham]], Greater London, to a DR Congolese father and an Angolan mother.<ref>{{cite web |title=2020/21 Premier League squads confirmed |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/1869523 |date=20 October 2020 |access-date=21 October 2020 |website=Premier League}}</ref><ref name="PremProfile"/><ref>{{cite web |date=9 July 2024 |title=Ezri Konsa |url=https://www.worldfootball.net/person/pe434384/ezri-konsa/ |access-date=13 November 2023 |website=HEIM:SPIEL}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{Cite web |url=https://www.londonnewsonline.co.uk/south-london-press-exclusive-interview-with-ezri-konsa-on-january-transfer-window-speculation-game-time-at-charlton-athletic-and-promotion-hopes/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181229233828/https://www.londonnewsonline.co.uk/south-london-press-exclusive-interview-with-ezri-konsa-on-january-transfer-window-speculation-game-time-at-charlton-athletic-and-promotion-hopes/ |url-status=usurped |archive-date=29 December 2018 |title=South London Press exclusive interview with Ezri Konsa – on January transfer window speculation, game time at Charlton Athletic and promotion hopes |last=Cawley |first=Richard |website=South London News |date=23 February 2018 |access-date=29 January 2019}}</ref> He attended [[Cumberland School|Cumberland Sports College]] and is a boyhood [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.]] supporter.<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cafc.co.uk/news/article/20120905-harris-academy-354776.aspx?pageView=full |title=Academies join forces |date=5 September 2012 |publisher=Charlton Athletic F.C.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170616173908/http://www.cafc.co.uk/news/article/20120905-harris-academy-354776.aspx?pageView=full|archive-date=16 June 2017|url-status=dead|access-date=16 June 2017}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Charlton Athletic===
Konsa began his career with [[Senrab F.C.|Senrab]] and joined [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] at the age of 11.<ref name=":0" /> He began a scholarship in July 2014 and progressed sufficiently to sign a "long term" professional contract on 11 December 2015.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cafc.co.uk:80/team/academy/ |title=Charlton Athletic FC Academy Player Profiles |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141124052048/http://www.cafc.co.uk/team/academy/ |archive-date=24 November 2014 |url-status=dead |access-date=5 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cafc.co.uk/news/article/charlton-athletic-new-contracts-academy-2846963.aspx |title=Academy trio sign new long-term contracts with Charlton Athletic |publisher=Charlton Athletic F.C. |date=11 December 2015|access-date=16 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170616174849/http://www.cafc.co.uk/news/article/charlton-athletic-new-contracts-academy-2846963.aspx|archive-date=16 June 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Eight days later, he received his maiden call into the [[First team (association football)|first-team]] squad for a [[EFL Championship|Championship]] match versus [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] and remained an unused [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] during the 4–0 defeat.<ref name=":1">{{cite web |title=Ezri Konsa – Aston Villa Defender |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/player/_/id/231859/ezri-konsa-ngoyo?season=2015 |access-date=4 August 2018 |website=ESPN}}</ref> Konsa was an unused substitute on one further occasion during the [[2015–16 Charlton Athletic F.C. season|2015–16 season]],<ref name=":1" /> which culminated in Charlton's relegation to [[EFL League One|League One]].<ref name=":2">{{cite web |title=Football Club History Database – Charlton Athletic |url=https://www.fchd.info/CHARLTOA.HTM |access-date=13 November 2023 |website=www.fchd.info}}</ref>

Konsa broke into the squad during the [[pre-season]] of their [[2016–17 Charlton Athletic F.C. season|2016–17 season]] and made his debut on 9 August 2016 with a start in a 1–0 [[EFL Cup]] first round defeat to [[Cheltenham Town F.C.|Cheltenham Town]].<ref name="CharltonProfile">{{cite web |title=Player Profile |url=https://www.cafc.co.uk/team/player/59492bc18e616/profile |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220215004010/https://www.cafc.co.uk/team/player/59492bc18e616/profile |archive-date=15 February 2022 |access-date=5 August 2018 |publisher=Charlton Athletic F.C.}}</ref><ref name="sb1617"/> He was a regular throughout the 2016–17 season and finished the campaign with 39 appearances.<ref name="sb1617"/> He also showed his versatility by deputising in [[Midfielder|midfield]] and at [[Full-back (association football)|full-back]].<ref name="CharltonProfile" /> For his efforts, Konsa was named the club's Young Player of the Year.<ref name="YPOTY">{{cite web |date=3 May 2017 |title=PLAYER OF THE YEAR : 2016/17 a great learning curve for award-winning Ezri Konsa |url=https://www.cafc.co.uk/news/view/595526ab7ff92/player-of-the-year-201617-a-great-learning-curve-for-award-winning-ezri-konsa |access-date=16 June 2017 |publisher=Charlton Athletic F.C.}}</ref> He signed a new three-year contract in March 2017 and was again a regular during the [[2017–18 Charlton Athletic F.C. season|2017–18 season]],<ref>{{cite web |title=NEWS {{!}} Academy graduate Ezri Konsa signs new, three-year contract |url=https://www.charltonafc.com/news/view/595526aa4defa/news-academy-graduate-ezri-konsa-signs-new-three-year-contract |date=17 March 2017 |access-date=16 June 2017 |website=Charlton Athletic F.C.}}</ref> making 47 appearances as Charlton reached the [[2018 English Football League play-offs#League One Semi-finals|League One play-off semi-finals]].<ref name=":2" /><ref name="sb1718" />

===Brentford===
On 12 June 2018, Konsa signed for Championship club [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] on a three-year contract, with the option of a further year, for an undisclosed fee,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.brentfordfc.com/news/2018/june/ezri-konsa-signs-for-brentford/ |title=Ezri Konsa signs for Brentford |access-date=4 August 2018 |publisher=Brentford F.C. |archive-date=26 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210226150902/https://www.brentfordfc.com/news/2018/june/ezri-konsa-signs-for-brentford/ |url-status=dead }}</ref> reported to be £2.5&nbsp;million.<ref name="Storer">{{cite web |url=https://www.football.london/brentford-fc/brentford-talking-points-konsa-mepham-15050616 |title=Brentford talking points: Konsa's quality, Mepham the leader |last=Storer |first=Tom |date=20 August 2018 |website=FootballLondon |access-date=4 February 2019}}</ref> He was a first choice in central defence throughout the [[2018–19 Brentford F.C. season|2018–19 season]] and scored the first senior goal of his career in a 3–0 victory over [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] on the final day.<ref name="No15">{{cite web |url=https://www.brentfordfc.com/news/2019/june/ezri-number-15-for-england/ |title=Ezri gets number 15 shirt for championships |publisher=Brentford F.C. |access-date=9 June 2019 |archive-date=4 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210204143856/https://www.brentfordfc.com/news/2019/june/ezri-number-15-for-england/ |url-status=dead }}</ref>

===Aston Villa===
On 11 July 2019, 21-year-old Konsa signed for newly promoted [[Premier League]] club [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]], for an undisclosed fee.<ref>{{cite web |title=Transfer News: Welcome Ezri Konsa |url=https://www.avfc.co.uk/News/2019/07/11/transfer-news-ezri%20konsa-arrives |access-date=11 July 2019 |website=Aston Villa F.C.}}</ref> The move reunited Konsa with [[Dean Smith (footballer, born 1971)|Dean Smith]], who signed him for Brentford one year earlier, and [[Richard O'Kelly]]. He scored on his debut for Villa in an EFL Cup tie against [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]] on 27 August 2019.<ref>{{cite news |date=27 August 2019|title=Carabao Cup: Crewe 1–6 Aston Villa |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49403071 |access-date=27 August 2019 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> On 21 January 2020, Konsa assisted [[Tyrone Mings]] to set up the winning goal in a 2–1 victory against [[Watford F.C.|Watford]].<ref>{{cite news |date=21 January 2020 |title=Aston Villa haul themselves out of bottom three with late win over Watford |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/jan/21/aston-villa-watford-premier-league-match-report |access-date=22 January 2020 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> He scored his first Premier League goal on 16 July 2020, in a 1–1 away draw at [[Everton F.C.|Everton]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Johnston |first=Neil |date=16 July 2020 |title=Everton 1–1 Aston Villa: Late Theo Walcott equaliser denies Villa crucial win |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/53343860 |access-date=16 July 2020 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>

On 2 April 2021, Konsa signed a contract extension with Aston Villa until 2026.<ref>{{cite web |date=2 April 2021 |title=Aston Villa is pleased to announce that Ezri Konsa has signed a contract extension until 2026 |url=https://www.avfc.co.uk/news/2021/april/Konsa-pens-contract-extension/ |access-date=2 April 2021 |website=Aston Villa F.C.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=2 April 2021 |title=Ezri Konsa: Aston Villa defender signs new deal until 2026 |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/56618103 |access-date=1 April 2025 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> On 5 December 2021, Konsa scored twice in a 2–1 Premier League victory over [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]], becoming the first defender to score twice in a Premier League match for Aston Villa since 2010.<ref>{{cite web |title=Aston Villa 2–1 Leicester City: Steven Gerrard secures win against his former Liverpool boss Brendan Rodgers |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/aston-villa-vs-leicester-city/report/446428|access-date=6 December 2021 |website=Sky Sports}}</ref>

On 15 May 2022, Konsa suffered a serious knee injury in a home game against [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]].<ref>{{cite web |date=18 May 2022 |title=The Presser: Gerrard quizzed ahead of Burnley |url=https://www.avfc.co.uk/news/2022/may/18/the-presser--gerrard-quizzed-ahead-of-burnley/ |access-date=1 April 2025 |website=Aston Villa F. C.}}</ref> Scans confirmed, that although Konsa would miss the remaining two games of the [[2021–22 Aston Villa F.C. season|2021–22 season]], he was expected to be fit again in August or September 2022.<ref>{{cite web |date=18 May 2022 |title=Ezri Konsa ruled out for up to 16 weeks |url=https://www.avfc.co.uk/news/2022/may/18/konsa-ruled-out-for-up-to-16-weeks/ |access-date=18 May 2022 |website=Aston Villa F. C.}}</ref>

Konsa returned from injury on the opening day of the [[2022–23 Aston Villa F.C. season|2022–23 season]] on 6 August 2022, and once again established himself as a first-team regular for Aston Villa.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bournemouth v Aston Villa, 2022/23 |url=https://www.premierleague.com/match/74912 |access-date=14 April 2023 |website=Premier League}}</ref> On 20 September 2023, he signed a new long-term contract at the club.<ref>{{cite web |date=20 September 2023 |title=Ezri Konsa pens new long-term Aston Villa contract |url=https://www.avfc.co.uk/news/2023/september/20/konsa-pens-long-term-contract/ |access-date=20 September 2023 |website=Aston Villa F. C.}}</ref> On 15 April 2025, he scored his first [[UEFA Champions League]] goal in a 3–2 victory over [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]] during the [[2024–25 UEFA Champions League knockout phase|quarter-finals]] of the competition.<ref>{{cite web |last=McNulty |first=Phil |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/ckgr4n77yy3t |title=Aston Villa 3–2 PSG |publisher=BBC Sport |date=15 April 2025 }}</ref>

On 6 November 2025, Konsa captained Aston Villa in a 2–0 [[UEFA Europa League]] victory over [[Maccabi Tel Aviv F.C.|Maccabi Tel Aviv]]. After the match, manager [[Unai Emery]] confirmed that Konsa had been made Villa's new vice captain, deputising [[John McGinn]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Townley |first=John |date=2025-11-06 |title=Unai Emery confirms big Emi Martinez decision after important Villa conversation |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/unai-emery-confirms-big-emi-32828225 |access-date=2025-11-07 |website=Birmingham Live |language=en}}</ref> On 20 May 2026, Konsa started in the [[2025–26 UEFA Europa League|2026 UEFA Europa League]] final, which Aston Villa won 3–0.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Freiburg 0-3 Aston Villa: Villans cruise past German side to win first European trophy since 1982 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/c893dkqjv00t |access-date=2026-05-21 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>

==International career==
===Youth===
Konsa was a member of the England squad that won the [[2017 FIFA U-20 World Cup]] with his only appearance of the tournament coming as a 93rd-minute substitute during the 3–1 semi-final victory over [[Italy national under-20 football team|Italy]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Academy Manager takes pride in Konsa and Lookman's World Cup triumph |url=https://www.charltonafc.com/news/view/595526ac1e3c2/academy-manager-takes-pride-in-konsa-and-lookmans-world-cup-triumph |access-date=9 January 2020 |website=Charlton Athletic F.C.}}</ref>

Konsa was named in the [[England national under-21 football team|under-21]] squad for the [[2018 Toulon Tournament]] and made two appearances.<ref name="Soccerway">{{cite web |url=https://uk.soccerway.com/players/ezri-konsa-ngoyo/431214/ |title=E. Konsa: Summary |website=Soccerway |publisher=Perform Group |access-date=13 November 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Ezri Konsa stars on England U21s debut |url=https://www.charltonafc.com/news/view/5b0e7f6562e73/ezri-konsa-stars-on-england-u21s-debut |access-date=5 August 2018 |website=harlton Athletic F.C.}}</ref> He was an unused substitute during the 2–1 victory over [[Mexico national under-20 football team|Mexico]] in the final.<ref name="Soccerway" /> Konsa scored his first international goal on his fourth cap, in a 7–0 [[2019 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification]] win over [[Andorra national under-21 football team|Andorra]] on 11 October 2018.<ref name="Soccerway" /> He was named in the squad for the tournament [[2019 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|finals]],<ref name="No15" /> but made just one appearance, as a substitute in the Young Lions' [[dead rubber]] final group stage match.<ref name="Soccerway" />

===Senior===
Konsa received his first call-up for the [[England national football team|England senior team]] in November 2023 ahead of their [[UEFA Euro 2024 qualifying]] matches against [[Malta national football team|Malta]] and [[North Macedonia national football team|North Macedonia]],<ref>{{Cite web |last=Walker |first=Andy |date=13 November 2023 |title=England men's squad updates: Lewis, Palmer and Konsa called up |url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2023/Nov/13/england-mens-squad-updates-november-internationals-2023 |publisher=The Football Association |access-date=13 November 2023}}</ref> but did not play in either match. He made his debut on 23 March 2024, as a 20th-minute substitute in a 1–0 defeat to [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] at [[Wembley Stadium]] in a [[friendly (association football)|friendly]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/68647860 |title=England 0–1 Brazil |first=Phil |last=McNulty |website=BBC Sport |date=23 March 2024 |access-date=23 March 2024}}</ref>

On 6 June 2024, Konsa was named in England's 26-man squad for [[UEFA Euro 2024]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cv22menk7dno |title=Eze & Wharton named in England squad for Euro 2024 |website=BBC Sport |date=6 June 2024 |access-date=6 June 2024}}</ref> He made his competitive debut in the [[UEFA Euro 2024 knockout stage#Round of 16|round of 16]] win over [[Slovakia national football team|Slovakia]], playing the second half of extra time after replacing [[Jude Bellingham]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/match/2036200--england-vs-slovakia/matchinfo/|title=England 2–1 Slovakia: Match Info|access-date=7 June 2024|website=UEFA}}</ref> In the quarter-final against [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]], he was selected to start in place of the suspended [[Marc Guéhi]], playing 78 minutes before being substituted for [[Cole Palmer]] as England eventually won via a [[penalty shootout]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Draper |first=Rob |date=6 July 2024 |title=England 1–1 Switzerland (5–3 pens): Euro 2024 quarter-final player ratings |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/article/2024/jul/06/england-1-1-switzerland-5-3-pens-euro-2024-quarter-final-player-ratings |access-date=7 June 2024 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

Konsa scored his first senior international goal, the third in a 5–0 [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification - UEFA Group K|2026 FIFA World Cup qualification]] victory away at [[Serbia national football team|Serbia]].<ref name=":3" />

== Style of play ==
A right-footed centre-back<ref>{{Cite news |last=Tanswell |first=Jacob |date=25 August 2025 |title=How playing two left-footed centre-backs sums up Aston Villa's problems |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/6571489/2025/08/25/aston-villa-brentford-defence-refresh-result/ |access-date=12 November 2025 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> who can also be deployed as a right-back,<ref>{{Cite web |last=Fish |first=Hal |date=31 March 2024 |title=The 12 best centre-backs who also play at full-back right now have been ranked |url=https://www.givemesport.com/the-best-centre-backs-who-also-play-at-fullback/ |access-date=12 November 2025 |website=GiveMeSport |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":4">{{Cite news |last=Tanswell |first=Jacob |date=8 June 2024 |title=Ezri Konsa's England inclusion may shock outsiders – but his versatility is invaluable |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/5374885/2024/06/06/ezri-konsa-england-euros-aston-villa/ |access-date=12 November 2025 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Konsa is considered a quick defender<ref>{{Cite web |last=Creamer |first=Matthew |date=15 November 2020 |title=Ezri Konsa is Developing Into a Quality Premier League Centre-Back |url=https://lastwordonsports.com/football/2020/11/15/ezri-konsa-is-developing-into-a-quality-premier-league-centre-back/ |access-date=12 November 2025 |website=Last Word on Football |language=en-US}}</ref> who frequently carries the ball up the field<ref name=":5">{{Cite web |date=26 January 2024 |title=The Great Wall of Villa Park: Ezri Konsa - Breaking The Lines |url=https://breakingthelines.com/player-analysis/the-great-wall-of-villa-park-ezri-konsa/ |access-date=12 November 2025 |language=en-GB}}</ref> and gets blocks in on shots.<ref name=":6">{{Cite news |last=Evans |first=Gregg |last2=Carey |first2=Mark |date=18 March 2021 |title=Analysed: Why the improved, unflustered Ezri Konsa deserved an England call-up |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/2451434/2021/03/18/ezri-konsa-england-aston-villa/ |access-date=12 November 2025 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> He is noted to have a high clean tackle percentage rate compared to other defenders, rarely going in for last-chance tackles,<ref name=":6" /> and in April 2024 he had a 91 percent tackle rate, the highest of any defender in the big five leagues.<ref name=":4" /> He is also noted as a player who frequently wins duels, both aerially and on the ground.<ref>{{Cite web |last= |date=7 November 2025 |title=Liverpool now chasing for 'one of the 'world's best CBs' |url=https://www.thefootballgroup.com/liverpool-now-chasing-for-one-of-the-worlds-best-cbs/ |access-date=12 November 2025 |website=The Football Group |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Wilkinson |first=Matthew |date=15 October 2025 |title=Chelsea should look to sign Liverpool target who shone for England, and it's not Marc Guehi |url=https://tbrfootball.com/chelsea-should-look-to-sign-liverpool-target-who-shone-for-england-and-its-not-marc-guehi/ |access-date=12 November 2025 |website=TBR Football |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name=":5" />

